Hey there! For my Instagram audience, I wanted to share some exciting news about the work I'm doing off stage. As some of you may know, I am involved with a nonprofit called @transhousingstlouis (aka THISTL), where I serve as one of the founders, president, and interim project manager.

Our focus is on advocating for trans-specific housing rights and bridging the gap between housing justice and trans liberation. In the past year, we conducted a qualitative needs analysis of our local trans and gender expansive community members, which we then presented to local government officials to help improve services for underserved communities.

From this effort, we launched a 6-week educational program in collaboration with the City of St Louis' treasurer's office, offering a stipend for trans individuals to learn valuable skills around financial literacy, renting, home ownership, legal rights, and more.

Today marked the last day of the program, and I am grateful for all the guest presenters who generously shared their expertise and support with our participants. Our nonprofit has given thousands of dollars in direct rental assistance to trans individuals in need, but this program is by far the most extensive one we've undertaken.

I am overjoyed that we successfully completed the course, and I can't wait to see what the future holds for our growing organization. Thank you for supporting our efforts to make a difference in our community!
May you be so lucky to endure today living your life as your truest self🧚🏾‍♂️🍀

It’s been a magical week in Ecuador exploring the Amazon rainforest and getting in touch with myself.  I’ve spent 9 days detoxing from social media and have spent a long time critically analyzing my past and potential err in maintenance of friendships and community. 

I’m so thankful to the Sápara people in Atatakuinjia for letting me and the group in to learn about ecological maintenance and a closeness to nature. 

I purchased this handcarved flute from the community and found so much tranquility in the sounds that it makes and I wanted to share.  I’ll be sharing more from this trip and open dialogue about individual & collective obligations of ecological sustainability…. But first here’s me playing the flute.

It’s the first day of Pride month and I’m excited and honored to be hosting a fundraiser at @drinkplatypus wearing my own designs! 🫣

Come hang with me at this fundraiser for @promomissouri and let’s do gay shit!!

TAKE ME BACK TO THE JUNGLE! 

I was truly captivated by the awe-inspiring wonders of the Amazon Rainforest, as I immersed myself in a profound exploration of the vital matter of indigenous land sovereignty. Amidst the relentless struggle against oil companies vying to seize sacred territories, my experiences revealed the profound connection between humanity and the natural world.

The disheartening reality of prioritizing profits derived from plastics, fossil fuels, and synthetic materials over the preservation of our ecological well-being is a challenging concept to grasp. We must recognize the urgent need to actively oppose land theft and the deforestation of these precious natural havens. By doing so, we afford ourselves the opportunity to revel in the extraordinary beauty that our planet so graciously offers.

It is beyond honorable to have been included in this write up of Queer St Louisans advocating for change in our local community. Thank you so much to @stlouismag for the write up and @stevenlouisbrawley @humankraemer @dieta_pepsi and @shiraberk for all the work you do

Today I leave for a 3 week adventure in Geneva Switzerland. I'm so exited to be going to the birthplace of yodeling.  One of the items on my bucket list is to yodel in the Swiss Alps.  I’m going to do research on international Queer policy reform and epistemic injustices of cross cultural communication in Queer advocacy work. 

Where should I go while in Geneva?? What should I do??
Guess where I am…. Wrong answers only!

A few days before I got to Paris the French police shot and killed Nahel Merzouk, a 17 year old boy of Algerian descent. This resulted in the uprising of French people against the racism and injustices militarized police inflict upon people of African, and Arab descent.  All over French speaking Europe riots, protests, and direct actions have been orchestrated against the racist and Islamaphobic violence. These demonstrations resulted in the heightened militarized police presence.

The violent abuse of power and institutional injustice people of color experience is not isolated in one country, but transcends virtually all national boundaries. With the American police’s origins being an entity to capture enslaved people that ran a way, to the Israeli Defense Fund (IDF) being created to kill Palestinians to expand borders, and the police of Nazi Germany, globally police are a reactive measure that improperly responds to perceived suspicion. 

When what makes you suspicious is your ethnic origin, and racial makeup many people of color are constantly surveilled.  These are some of the moments I captured so far showcasing the aftermath. 

When we say”ALL” cops are bastards that ”ALL” is not contingent on an individual state or municipality but the militarization of police is the bastardization of human rights on a global scale.

Tomorrow is my birthday, and I'm going to Les Diablerets, Switzerland, to hang out in the snowy Swiss Alps. 

What do you think the chances are of me recording videos yodeling the Alps?
Yodeling on my birthday!!!

This last week has been wonderful in my world of studying international Queer policy, language and culture with @webstergeneva in Switzerland. I’ve had the joy of visiting the capital city of Bern to interview the country’s leading lesbian advocacy organization @swisslos . Later I met and  interviewed members of @ilgaworld who is one of the leading international organizations on protecting the right of everyone no matter their Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity. 

It’s been a very full week and in top of the academics I led a makeup workshop with @swissburlesqueacademy which was absolutely darling. 

Looking forward to let the information settle and get a deeper analysis of Queer advocacy from a global perspective to help create a more harmonious and affirming place in St Louis when in get back next week.

After 9 remarkable years of Qu’art, it's time for an exciting rebirth. Qu’art, a St. Louis-based organization I founded in 2014, has been a dedicated champion of diversity within Queer art and a powerful platform for driving social change. Over the course of nearly a decade, we collaborated with more than 300 artists from around the world, orchestrated impactful direct actions, conducted educational programs, and engaged in critical political debates.

All of these incredible efforts will now continue under a new banner: PQAM, which stands for the Progressive Queer Art Movement. During this transitional phase, our organization is undergoing a restructuring process with a primary focus on becoming a 501(c)(4) non-profit entity, geared toward shaping policies and engaging in political discourse that amplifies the Black Queer Gender Expansive Eco-Feminist perspective within the broader context of intersectional liberation.

In this pivotal moment, we are actively seeking passionate individuals to join our board of directors, individuals who can play a pivotal role in guiding our organization through this transformational journey, charting a clear and impactful path toward change in the St. Louis area.

Email quartstl@gmail.com or message @queer_progress_ to get involved

This last month I’ve watch a lot of luck fade. Glad I found some fairy magic out in the garden too help me charge up on the good luck vibes. I wonder what magic is on the horizon! 🧚🏾‍♂️🍀🧚🏾‍♂️

What is it like to be neurodiverse and need more stimulation than most? To be labeled as too much that you’re only good in small doses? 

These questions and the consequent emotions inspired me to write this song called “The Undergrow.” 

When I perform it live, so many people come up to me and tell me that with them being neurodiverse they personally relate.  While this song is in a sense a lamentation, it is so validating knowing so many people are also navigating the same thing. It’s grounding knowing you’re not alone. 

It reminds me to be in the frame of mind that we’re not broken but more like a radio station on a different frequency. That others need to take the time to tune in to truly enjoy our magnificence. 

“THE UNDERGROW” comes out OCT 6th on all streaming platforms!  Go stream it and then come sing the words with me at @getfaeded later that night!!

I’m beyond honored to have been invited to @slu_official to receive the Stacy Harris award for trans and nonbinary visibility.  Personally I think awards are a bit awkward as it focuses too much on the individual, but I accept this as thanks and extend my gratitude to all those all the way that helped me keep my head above water.

When I was a teenager I was kicked out of the house for doing drag.  I scurried around homeless for a while and then @paris.amor found me and took me under her wing.  Together we’d scrape up money and stay in cheap motels and in an out of section 8 housing performing every chance we could to survive. 

She introduced me to African dance, to ballroom, and helped me find myself as a drag artist.  She gave me a new family of Black Queer artists with the House of Amor.  For years I studied every slight movement of her chaotic musicality, I integrated her dance styles and her art profoundly shaped who I’d become. 

I’m drowning in disbelief thinking she’s gone… I’m stuck knowing that I’ve learned everything I could have learned from my drag mom. 

Thank you so much for believing in me when no one else did…. I’m forever in your debt and I’ll carry your memory until I fade into a memory my myself. 

I hope you found peace Paris.

During the Indigenous week of mourning, we encourage our community to stand in solidarity with Indigenous peoples across the United States, Canada, and beyond, advocating for Land Back Everywhere. Drag artists across the world are uniting in a front against colonialism and are using their collective voice to say “Not in our name”. This is in direct response to the illegal occupation of Palestinian land and a demand to end the rhetorical and physical genocidal violence Palestinians are subjected to everyday. 

Drag itself is more than an art form but drag performers are a pillar of Queer culture and communal development.  We are the curators of Queer discourse and I wholly believe that it is our duty to shepherd the community to conversations of justice, equity, and peace.  And for that I have added my name to this list of other drag artists who see a need to use drag as a tool to instigate change. 

To read the full open letter of Drag artists for Palestine, or add your your name please click the link in my bio. 

For additional resources check out @queersinpalestine, @bdsnationalcommittee, and @alqaws_org

As a kid, I told myself I wanted to be an internationally touring performer and use art to connect with people all over the world. I would then use that knowledge and share it with the future generations, using said knowledge as a tool for justice freeing the most marginalized. 

In that I knew that becoming an academic would be what was needed and so I decided to apply to grad school programs.  Over the last couple months I've diligently given my everything into an application to get into a PhD program in philosophy. 

You might have seen me back stage working on research, asking you to read my work, or been my cats who wanted me to stop so I can pet them. 

Today I filed my application to a PhD program and I'm one step closer to becoming Dr. Maximus Amadeus Glamour. ☺️

I have been really looking at the qualitative aspects of time recently and how it's more than moments, but sequential experiences bent into another. While thinking about time I've realized Ive been  struggling admiring the past while anticipating the future, but trying to stay present in the moment. 

This is definitely a goal for next year to admire the intrinsic value of things as they currently exist in lieu of their prospected trajectory in a world where so many variables change outcomes at the whim of the fates. 

I'd love to know what kind of stuff y'all do to remain present and grounded yet not neglecting the lessons of the past or striving for goals in the future? How do you find stillness in the present when it lasts less than a second before it's gone?
